{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614858"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:49:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:49:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16375"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16375"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.21,0.13,0.04,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9066"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116503"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9066"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16375"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98496"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7160"},{"type":"tags","id":"10333"},{"type":"tags","id":"10336"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21554"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21557"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116503"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe corticospinal (pyramidal) tract is the major descending pathway controlling voluntary movement. Most of its fibres cross from one side to the other at a specific point in the central nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the location of pyramidal decussation in the corticospinal tract?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Caudal medulla","Spinal cord","Cervicomedullary junction","Cerebrum","Rostral medulla"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecaudal medulla\u003C/strong\u003E is the site of pyramidal decussation, where approximately 90% of corticospinal tract fibres cross from one side to the other. After crossing, these fibres continue as the lateral corticospinal tract.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pyramidal decussation does not occur in the \u003Cstrong\u003Espinal cord\u003C/strong\u003E as this is below the level of decussation. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecervicomedullary junction\u003C/strong\u003E while close to the actual location, is anatomically distinct from the site of crossing. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebrum\u003C/strong\u003E is where the tract originates but not where it crosses to the contralateral side. The \u003Cstrong\u003Erostral medulla\u003C/strong\u003E is above the level of decussation where the fibres have not yet crossed. The remaining 10% of fibres that do not cross at the pyramidal decussation continue ipsilaterally as the anterior corticospinal tract. Some of these fibres will eventually cross at the spinal cord level where they synapse.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The pyramidal decussation occurs at the junction between the medulla oblongata and spinal cord, where approximately 90% of corticospinal tract fibres cross to the contralateral side.","The crossed fibres form the lateral corticospinal tract, while uncrossed fibres form the anterior corticospinal tract."],"references":["Natali AL, Reddy V, Bordoni B. Neuroanatomy, Corticospinal Cord Tract. 2023 Aug 14. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30571044","Perez MA, Cohen LG. The corticospinal system and transcranial magnetic stimulation in stroke. Top Stroke Rehabil. 2009 Jul-Aug;16(4):254-69. doi: 10.1310/tsr1604-254. PMID: 19740731; PMCID: PMC4886556.Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98496"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16375"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98496"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-29T15:40:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-29T15:42:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9066"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116503"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[]